        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity:
1.Source flux : The existing SMA data of the SDP81 lens system indicate a total flux density of 78±8 mJy and a peak value of ≈8 mJy per SMA beam. The interesting feature in the partial Einstein ring has a peak continuum flux density of 2.4 mJy per SMA beam (Bussmann et al. 2013). Considering the spatial resolution of 0.6" FWHM for the available SMA map and the goal spatial resolution of 0.15" with ALMA, the peak flux density of the interesting feature is expected to be 0.15 mJy per ALMA beam.

2.Source angular size: 
Source angular size : The intended target consists of 4 gravitationally lensed images, three of which are partially blended in the SMA map (Negrello et al. 2010). The maximum angular separation between the multiply-lensed images is ≈6 arcsec, but the largest smooth structure in the object (lower part of Einstein ring in Fig. 2) is no more than 2.5 arcsec across. There is no additional smooth structure (like a complete Einstein ring) expected from the lensing system . Moreover, the SMA map is produced from a collection of data using subcompact to very extended configurations, which would recover smooth structure up to 6 arcsec, if such structure existed. This means that the entire emission from this system can be recovered with a single ALMA configuration.

3.Significance (SNR) : The existing SMA 880 μm data (i.e. directly comparable to band 7) indicates an integrated flux density of 78±8 mJy with a peak of ≈8 mJy per SMA beam, where the rms noise equals 0.6 mJy per SMA beam (Negrello et al. 2010). The interesting feature in the map has a flux density of 2.4 mJy per beam. In order to get an ALMA map with slightly better quality than the existing SMA map, and ≈4 times better resolution, we are aiming for a sensitivity of 0.03 mJy per ALMA beam, which guarantees a significant (S/N=5) detection of the blob (the SMA map gives S/N=4). The expected ratio of the global flux peak in the SDP lens system (≈0.5 mJy per ALMA beam) to the rms noise (0.03 mJy per ALMA beam) is ≈17, i.e. an acceptable dynamical range. 

Imaging:
1.Figure 2d included in the scientific justification file represents the reconstructed map of one of the multiple images in a four-image gravitational lens with fluxes similar to those in SDP81. This image was produced using CASA simulations with the proposed ALMA settings and a 'briggs' weighting (robust=0.0). The quality of the reconstructed image seems perfectly adequate for our purposes. 

2. Source size vs. primary beam size: Given the angular size of the source, which is extended to 6" at most, and the primary beam size of band 7 (&gt;18"), the source does not extend beyond the central 1/3 of the primary beam, therefore loss of sensitivity towards the beam edges is not expected to affect the data.

Correlator Setup:
1.Total bandwidth: Since the goal is to study the thermal emission from a lensed sub-mm galaxy, the bandwidth is set to the single continuum option in the OT. Accordingly, the total bandwidth adopted in simulations by CASA equals 7.5GHz, considering all four basebands of each 2GHz in width.

2. Spectral Window placement: The standard spectral windows for B7 are chosen. This places all basebands where there are no significant atmospheric features. Also, to make sure that the goal sensitivity is achieved in the final data set, the baseband at the highest frequency, i.e. the least sensitive one, is chosen as the representative frequency (350.5GHz).</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
