    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The cold dark matter model predicts that all massive galaxies should be surrounded by large numbers of dark matter substructures in the dwarf-galaxy mass range. While some of these likely host the satellite galaxies we see in the Local Group, others must have remained completely dark and are still awaiting discovery. High-resolution observations of gravitationally lensed galaxies can reveal such substructures regardless of their stellar content, and a few such detections have already been made. Here, we strive to make the first ALMA detection of a dark matter substructure in the dwarf-galaxy mass range, by targeting the lensed sub-mm galaxy SDP81 for which lower-resolution data obtained with the SMA gives tentative evidence for a small-scale perturbation in the symmetry of the lens. This feature may be attributed to a very faint (M/L_V &gt; 100), relatively massive (M&gt;1e9-1e10 Msolar) substructure in the halo of the z~0.3 lens galaxy. The proposed ALMA map of the SDP81 system will allow us to confirm or rule out the substructure lensing interpretation and determine the mass of the substructure. Luminosity limits from HST images will also allow us to constrain its mass-to-light ratio.</prp:abstract>
